To self-host BookStack, the most stable and modern method is using the LinuxServer.io Docker image. It simplifies the complex PHP/database dependencies into a single deployment. 
BookStack Docker Compose Template 
Create a file named docker-compose.yml and paste the following. Replace placeholders like <PASS> with secure strings: 
A Docker Compose template to launch BookStack typically involves defining two services: one for the BookStack application and another for the MariaDB database. The BookStack service uses the lscr.io/linuxserver/bookstack:latest image and requires environment variables for PUID, PGID, timezone, application URL, and database connection details. It maps a local volume for configuration and exposes port 6875. The MariaDB service uses the lscr.io/linuxserver/mariadb:latest image, also requiring PUID, PGID, and timezone environment variables, along with MySQL root password, database name, user, and password. It maps a volume for database storage and is set to restart unless stopped. Both services are linked with a depends_on configuration. You can find example docker-compose.yml templates for BookStack from sources such as buymeacoffee.com and OmicX. 
After creating the docker-compose.yml file, you can launch the containers using docker-compose up -d. BookStack can then be accessed via your browser at http://<your-server-ip>:6875. Initial login uses default admin credentials (email: admin@admin.com, password: password), which should be changed immediately for security. 
For integration into an AI stack, BookStack includes diagrams.net integration, provides a rich API for adding documentation programmatically, and uses a "Shelves -> Books -> Chapters" structure for organization. BookStack does not sync with a Git repository, storing content in its database. If Git synchronization is needed, Wiki.js might be a suitable alternative. 
