and then i can setup permissions to allow/dissalow public access on a per page basis?
Yes, BookStack allows you to precisely control public access at the Shelf, Book, Chapter, or Page level. This is ideal for keeping your internal AI architecture private while making specific tutorials or project overviews public. 
How to Configure Selective Public Access
To set this up, you use a "Whitelist" approach: 
Enable Public Viewing: In your BookStack Settings, turn on the "Allow public viewing" master switch.
Restrict the Public Role: Navigate to Settings > Roles and edit the "Public" role. Uncheck all "View" permissions. Now, by default, a public visitor sees nothing.
Grant Specific Access:
Go to the specific Book or Page you want to make public.
Click the Permissions action (usually in the top-right menu).
Check "Enable Custom Permissions".
Find the "Public" role in the list and check "View".
Uncheck "Inherit defaults" for "Everyone Else" if you want to be extra strict. 
Key Permission Behaviors
Cascading: Permissions set at the Book level automatically apply to all Chapters and Pages within it, unless you override them individually.
Shelves: Permissions on a Shelf do not automatically cascade to the Books on it (due to books being able to sit on multiple shelves), but there is a button to "Copy Permissions to Books" on the shelf permission page.
Discovery: If you make a Page public but the parent Book private, the visitor will need the direct link to the page, as they won't be able to browse through the Book's table of contents. 
